        output='Based on the provided text, here are the details regarding the Space segment\'s launch cadence, number of launches, Starship development milestones, and government contract details:\n\n### **1. Launch Cadence**\n*   **Falcon 9 Transition:** While the Falcon 9 launch cadence has steadily increased over recent years, the company expects Falcon 9 launches to decrease over time as it transitions to Starship.\n*   **Starship\'s Step-Function Change:** Starship is designed to fundamentally transform launch cadence, enabling rapid turnaround times akin to commercial aviation and allowing for multiple launches per day at reduced costs. \n*   **Requirements for High Cadence:** Achieving the targeted high-rate cadence for Starship requires significant capital and operational milestones, including securing land for high-rate launch sites, scaling vehicle/engine production, building co-located propellant production facilities (air separation and methane liquefaction), securing sufficient power, and obtaining FAA regulatory approvals.\n*   **Reusability as a Driver:** Innovations like catching the first-stage booster with "chopstick" arms on the launch tower are specifically intended to facilitate rapid refurbishment and high-cadence return-to-launch-site operations.\n\n### **2. Number of Launches**\n*   **Overall Historical Metrics:** As of March 31, 2026, the company has completed approximately 650 orbital space launches (delivering ~7,400 metric tons to orbit), with over 540 of those flown on flight-proven Falcon rockets. In 2025 alone, 170 missions were completed across Falcon and Starship vehicles.\n*   **Falcon 9:** \n    *   Approximately 620 orbital launches as of March 31, 2026.\n    *   **2025:** 165 launches (157 flight-proven boosters).\n    *   **Q1 2026:** 40 launches (39 flight-proven boosters).\n    *   **Year-over-Year Totals:** 96 (2023), 134 (2024), and 165 (2025).\n*   **Falcon Heavy:** 11 launches as of March 31, 2026, maintaining a 100% mission success rate.\n*   **Starship:** 11 flight tests executed to date, with a 12th flight test scheduled.\n*   **Customer vs. Internal Launches (Falcon):**\n    *   *2023:* 33 customer / 63 internal\n    *   *2024:* 45 customer / 89 internal\n    *   *2025:* 43 customer / 122 internal\n    *   *Q1 2025:* 12 customer / 24 internal\n    *   *Q1 2026:* 7 customer / 33 internal\n\n### **3. Starship Development Milestones**\n*   **Payload Capacity:** First launched in 2023, Starship V3 is designed to deliver 100 metric tons to Earth\'s orbit in a fully reusable configuration. Future generations (potentially Starship V4) are being designed to double this capacity to 200 metric tons.\n*   **Flight Testing & Timeline:** 11 flight tests have been executed. A 12th test is scheduled to debut the next-generation Starship vehicle, Super Heavy booster, next-evolution Raptor engine, and a newly designed pad at Starbase. Payload delivery to orbit is expected to commence in the second half of 2026.\n*   **Technical & Reusability Achievements:**\n    *   Catching and reusing the Super Heavy first-stage booster using the launch tower\'s "chopstick" arms.\n    *   Returning the upper stage within three meters of its intended landing point.\n    *   Transferring approximately 5 metric tons of cryogenic propellant between tanks in space (a first-of-its-kind operation).\n    *   Successful in-space relights of Raptor engines and multiple controlled reentries through Earth\'s atmosphere.\n*   **Upcoming Milestones:** Catching the upper stage and demonstrating full in-orbit propellant transfer capabilities. *(Note: The text specifies that full upper-stage reusability and in-orbit refueling are not required to deploy V3 and V2 Mobile satellites to Low-Earth Orbit).*\n\n### **4. Government Contract Details**\n*   **Primary Provider Status:** The company is the primary launch provider for the U.S. government, serving agencies including NASA and the National Reconnaissance Office (NRO).\n*   **National Security Space Launch (NSSL):** In 2025, the company launched 11 of 12 NSSL medium and heavy-lift missions. Falcon Heavy was certified for NSSL operations in 2019.\n*   **NASA Missions:** \n    *   Launched all five U.S. crew and cargo missions to the International Space Station (ISS) in 2025.\n    *   Revenue was boosted by an increase in NASA Cargo Resupply Services (CRS) for additional ISS missions.\n    *   Falcon Heavy is contracted for critical NASA weather satellites, interplanetary probes (Europa Clipper to Jupiter, Dragonfly to Saturn), and the Nancy Grace Roman telescope.\n*   **Department of War:** The text notes increased revenue from a "U.S. Department of War" contract, which helped offset EBITDA decreases driven by Starship R&D expenses.\n*   **Contract Structure & Revenue Recognition:** "Launch and Development" revenue is derived from fixed-price government contracts ranging from 1 to 14 years. Revenue is recognized over time using the cost-to-cost input method, as the work creates an asset with no alternative use and the company holds an enforceable right to payment. (Inter-segment launches for internal Starlink satellites do not generate recognized revenue; costs are capitalized instead).',
