    tool_output=ToolOutput(
        output="Based on the provided S-1 excerpts, here are the depreciation schedules, useful life estimates, and asset composition details for satellites, launch vehicles, data centers, and GPU hardware (classified as servers and networking equipment).\n\n### 1. General Depreciation Methodology\n* **Standard Assets:** Depreciated primarily using the **straight-line method** over their estimated useful lives.\n* **Flight Vehicles & Spacecraft:** Depreciated based on the **expected number of average flights** rather than a time-based straight-line schedule.\n* **Leasehold Improvements:** Depreciated over the shorter of their estimated useful lives or the related lease term.\n* **Capitalization vs. Expense:** Routine maintenance is expensed as incurred. Significant refurbishments, renewals, and enhancements that extend an asset's life or functionality are capitalized and depreciated ratably. Interest is capitalized during the construction of significant long-term projects (e.g., AI data centers).\n\n---\n\n### 2. Satellites\n* **Depreciation Schedule:** Straight-line method over the estimated useful life.\n* **Useful Life Estimates:** \n  * **Broadband satellites:** 5 years.\n  * **First-generation mobile satellites:** 3 years.\n  * **General Range:** 3 to 5 years.\n  * *Factors considered:* Engineering studies, historical on-orbit performance, propellant life, orbit-raise timing, utilization patterns, design enhancements, and planned transitions to newer technology.\n* **Asset Composition (Gross PP&E):**\n  * **Dec 31, 2024:** $7,591 million\n  * **Dec 31, 2025:** $11,949 million\n  * **Mar 31, 2026:** $12,893 million\n* **Sensitivity:** A 1-year change in the average useful life of satellite assets would impact operating income by approximately $480 million (for full-year 2025) and $170 million (for Q1 2026).\n\n---\n\n### 3. Launch Vehicles (Flight Vehicle Hardware)\n* **Depreciation Schedule:** Depreciated over the **expected number of average flights** per vehicle.\n* **Useful Life Estimates:**\n  * **General Range:** 5 to 25 flights.\n  * **Falcon 9 / Falcon Heavy Boosters:** Engineered and demonstrated to support up to 40 flights, but the **maximum accounting useful life is capped at 25 flights**. This conservative estimate accounts for the strategic transition to Starship (reducing future Falcon demand) and government contract restrictions that sometimes prohibit using boosters flown more than 5 times.\n  * *Factors considered:* Recovery/refurbishment success rates, refurbishment economics, customer acceptance limits, and anticipated retirement timing.\n  * **Starship:** Currently in the development stage; the majority of costs are **expensed to R&D as incurred** rather than capitalized.\n  * **Inventory vs. PP&E:** Reusable components (boosters, fairings, Merlin engines, Dragon capsules) are classified as PP&E. Non-reusable components (second stages) are recorded as Inventory.\n* **Asset Composition (Gross PP&E):**\n  * **Dec 31, 2024:** $1,577 million\n  * **Dec 31, 2025:** $1,689 million\n  * **Mar 31, 2026:** $1,459 million\n* **Sensitivity:** A change of +/- 5 average remaining flights would *not* have a material impact on operating income for 2025 or Q1 2026.\n\n---\n\n### 4. Data Centers (Data Center Infrastructure)\n* **Depreciation Schedule:** Straight-line method over the estimated useful life.\n* **Useful Life Estimates:** 20 to 25 years.\n* **Asset Composition (Gross PP&E):**\n  * **Dec 31, 2024:** $224 million\n  * **Dec 31, 2025:** $2,960 million\n  * **Mar 31, 2026:** $2,965 million\n* **Construction-in-Progress (CIP):** A significant portion of ongoing data center expansion is held in CIP ($4,604M at end of 2025; surging to $14,045M by Q1 2026) and is not yet depreciated. The company capitalized $169 million in interest for AI data centers in 2025, and $7 million in Q1 2026.\n\n---\n\n### 5. GPU Hardware (Servers and Networking Equipment)\n* **Depreciation Schedule:** Straight-line method over the estimated useful life.\n* **Useful Life Estimates:** 5 to 6 years.\n* **Asset Composition (Gross PP&E):**\n  * **Dec 31, 2024:** $6,892 million\n  * **Dec 31, 2025:** $22,694 million\n  * **Mar 31, 2026:** $23,850 million\n* **Financial Impact:** The massive scaling of GPU hardware and AI data center infrastructure is the primary driver behind the AI segment's surging depreciation expenses, contributing heavily to a $3,888 million YoY increase in AI R&D expenses and a $1,533 million YoY increase in AI operating losses in Q1 2026.\n\n---\n\n### Impairment & Disposal Policies\n* **Evaluation:** Assets are evaluated for impairment at the lowest level with identifiable cash flows whenever events indicate the carrying value may not be recoverable (e.g., technological obsolescence, damaged hardware, or facility consolidation).\n* **Recent Charges:** \n  * **2024/2025:** Recorded impairments for damaged flight vehicles (Space segment) and abandoned/damaged satellite hardware (Connectivity segment).\n  * **2023/2024:** Recorded impairments for leasehold improvements and office equipment due to AI segment facility consolidations (Restructuring charges).\n* **Routine Losses:** Scrapping, gateway decommissions, and routine operational losses are charged directly to Cost of Revenue or SG&A.",
